My limited exposure to Lua suggests that different communities follow different conventions. For example, MediaWiki uses boolean function names that do not start with is, whereas the World of Warcraft API follows the `IsXXXX` pattern.\r\n\r\n![image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d708621d-6496-45d5-8677-35e5773e9685)\r\n\r\nOpenDAL, which focuses on object storage, remains closely aligned with file APIs in standard libraries. For example, Ruby's standard library extensively uses `IO#exists?`. An ergonomic API benefits both developers and language models. For this reason, I would recommend following the conventions of the binding languages standard library.\r\n\r\nIn the case of Lua, style guides [^1][^2] suggest using `is_exist` rather than `exist`. It simply includes a `Content-Range` header specifying the range of the returned content.\n\nI tested it locally and find that the server does return correct `content-length`:\n\n```shell\n:) curl \'http://localhost:3000/gridwatch_2023-01-08.parquet\' -H \'Range: bytes=4-138724\' -v\n* Host localhost:3000 was resolved.\n* IPv6: ::1\n* IPv4: 127.0.0.1\n*   Trying [::1]:3000...\n* Connected to localhost (::1) port 3000\n* using HTTP/1.x\n> GET /gridwatch_2023-01-08.parquet HTTP/1.1\n> Host: localhost:3000\n> Accept: */*\n> Accept-Language: en-US,en;q=0.9\n> Connection: keep-alive\n> DNT: 1\n> Origin: https://xuanwo.io\n> Range: bytes=4-138724\n> Sec-Fetch-Dest: empty\n> Sec-Fetch-Mode: cors\n> Sec-Fetch-Site: cross-site\n> User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/133.0.0.0 Safari/537.36 Edg/133.0.0.0\n> sec-ch-ua: "Not(A:Brand";v="99", "Microsoft Edge";v="133", "Chromium";v="133"\n> sec-ch-ua-mobile: ?0\n> sec-ch-ua-platform: "Linux"\n>\n* Request completely sent off\n< HTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content\n< Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *\n< Access-Control-Allow-Headers: *\n< Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true\n< Access-Control-Allow-Private-Network: true\n< Content-Length: 138721\n< Content-Disposition: inline; filename="gridwatch_2023-01-08.parquet"\n< Accept-Ranges: bytes\n< ETag: "9fd6c7db3d0a71c6bfedd73034904a4ff3c0d3dc"\n< Content-Type: binary/octet-stream\n< Last-Modified: Wed, 10 Jan 2025 12:00:00 GMT\n< access-control-allow-methods: GET,HEAD\n< Vary: Origin, Access-Control-Request-Headers, Access-Control-Request-Method\n< Content-Range: bytes 4-138724/29300729\n< Date: Tue, 04 Mar 2025 07:00:58 GMT\n< Connection: keep-alive\n< Keep-Alive: timeout=5\n<\nWarning: Binary output can mess up your terminal. Sorry, I'm not familiar with web technologies. \n\nBased on my understanding, when the server returns 206, it is legal for the server to return partial content no matter what `content-length` is set in the header. For example, if the client request ranges from 1-256, the server may respond 1-128 bytes but still with `content-length` set to 256. \n\nSo, a proper way to handle this is to \n\n1. send range request\n2. get 206 responses and check the data length \n3. if the data length is shorter than requested, issue another range request and return to 1. Otherwise, break. \n\n\nAlso, this is based on my observation of Chrome/Chromium. I don't know if other browsers behave the same way. That\'s said that we must add new features in a way that aligns with out vision: **One Layer, All Storage.** We should do our best to avoid exposing any storage service-specific details in our public API, such as in `Operator` or `OpCopy`.\n\nHaving an API looks like the following is confusing:\n\n```rust\nop.copy_with(src, dst).bucket("test").region("us-west-1").await\n```\n\nThat\'s why I believe adding `bucket` and `region` to `OpCopy` is not a good idea. These are configuration values specific to some storage services and are not relevant to other services. Additionally, this approach lacks extensibility, as it should also accommodate `SSE` settings effectively.\n\nOne possible idea is adding new config values in `CosConfig` like `copy_source: Box<CosConfig>`, but I\'m not sure if it\'s good enough.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/apache/opendal/issues/comments/2692018921/reactions', 'total_count': 1, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 1}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}]

'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'body': 'Hi, @Xuanwo , thank you very much for your suggestions. I think we can first list some common services that support checksum algorithms, which may include the supported checksum algorithms, the use of checksum algorithms in different read and write methods, the scope of data verification, etc. I would be happy to find and provide a list like this.\n\nIn addition, after choosing some common checksum algorithms, maybe these services will initially just rely on these common functions and expose them to users by setting configuration like we do now, and then consider refactoring this part by possibly adding layers; or perhaps from the beginning, the most general design considerations are used to determine the future application mode of checksum in OpenDAL, and implement it on this basis.\n\nI think the advantage of the first approach is that we can implement checksum for the most commonly used services first and accumulate knowledge for future general designs in the process. The advantage of the second approach is that if we design it clearly from the beginning, we can avoid repeated implementation.\n\nThese are some of my simple ideas, and hope to get any suggestions. I have checked those cases and am sure that they work as expected.\n\nThe `operation` itself is an enum, and each variant has its own static string. The conversion won't cause any memory leaks externally.\n\nThe `Scheme::Custom` is a bit tricky since it allows users to create a memory leak by repeatedly calling `Scheme::from_str(uuid::Uuid::new_v4())`. However, I personally think this is acceptable and ultimately up to the user's discretion. I will add some comments to this function to inform users about the potential issuewhen they use this API to construct a `Scheme` for custom services, they will receive a static string internally.", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/apache/opendal/issues/comments/2652561940/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}]
